Trump and the Economy
New York—Financial markets have finally awakened to the reality that Trump is the President of the United States.
The world has endured two years of unfiltered tweets and public statements from this most powerful person on the globe, and the obvious question is, what has kept this going for so long?
On one hand, until now, investors have assumed that Trump only talks the talk but doesn't walk the walk.
As long as he implements tax cuts, deregulation, and other policies favorable to the corporate sector and shareholders, they are willing to give him the benefit of the doubt.
Many people believe that eventually, the "adults in the room" will rein in Trump and ensure that government policies do not go too far.
This assumption was somewhat confirmed during the first year of Trump's presidency, a period during which economic growth and corporate profit expectations — thanks to the upcoming tax cuts and deregulation — led to a strong performance in the stock market.
In 2017, American stock indices rose by more than 20%.
But in 2018, the situation deteriorated rapidly, especially in the last few months.
Despite corporate profits increasing by more than 20% (thanks to tax cuts), the American stock market fluctuated throughout most of the year and has now sharply declined.
Currently, various indices are in correction territory (i.e., down 10% from recent highs), and the tech stock indices (such as the Nasdaq) have fallen into a bear market (down 20% or more).
Although the increase in volatility in financial markets reflects concerns about China, Italy, and other eurozone economies, as well as key emerging economies, the recent turmoil is because of Trump.
At the beginning of the year, Trump implemented reckless tax cuts, which resulted in higher long-term interest rates, pushing an economy already near full employment to its peak.
By February, concerns about inflation rising above the Federal Reserve's target of 2% led to the first safety-seeking rush of 2018.
Then, Trump launched a trade war against China and other important American trading partners.
Concerns about government protectionist policies have fluctuated throughout the year, but are now reaching new peaks.
Recent US actions toward China seem to be preparing for a comprehensive trade, economic, and geopolitical cold war.
Another concern is that Trump's other policies may lead to stagflation (weakened growth while inflation increases).
After all, Trump is preparing to restrict foreign direct investment inflows and has implemented broad immigration restrictions, which will hinder the growth of the labor supply in the context of increasingly severe aging of the workforce and skill mismatch.
Moreover, the Trump administration has yet to propose an infrastructure plan to stimulate private sector productivity or accelerate the transition to a green economy.
On Twitter and other occasions, Trump constantly criticizes corporate hiring, production, investment, and pricing behaviors, especially technology companies, which have already faced widespread opposition and increasingly fierce competition from Chinese rivals.
Emerging markets have also been impacted by U.S. policies.
Fiscal stimulus and monetary policy tightening have increased short-term and long-term interest rates, strengthening the dollar.
As a result, emerging economies have experienced capital flight and an increase in the value of dollar-denominated debt.
Emerging economies heavily reliant on exports have suffered losses due to falling commodity prices, and even countries with only indirect trade relations with China have felt the impact of the trade war.
Even Trump's oil policy has created volatility.
Restarting sanctions against Iran by the US raised oil prices, and then the US government revoked exemptions and intimidated Saudi Arabia to increase oil production, leading to a sharp drop in oil prices.
Although American consumers benefited from low oil prices, the stock prices of US energy companies could not hold up.
In addition, excessive oil price fluctuations are detrimental to both producers and consumers, as they hinder wise investment and consumption decisions.
More seriously, now it is evident that almost all the benefits from last year's tax cuts have flowed to the corporate sector, rather than to households in the form of higher real (inflation-adjusted) wages.
This means that household consumption may soon slow down, further affecting the economy.
However, the main reason for the recent sharp drop in U.S. and global stock markets in the last quarter was Trump's own statements and actions.
Worse than the prominent risk of a full-scale trade war with China (although he recently reached a "ceasefire" with Chinese President Xi Jinping) is Trump's public criticism of the Federal Reserve. His criticism began in spring 2018, when the U.S. economic growth rate was above 4%.
Because of these earlier criticisms, the markets became extremely nervous when the Federal Reserve correctly decided to raise interest rates this month, while hinting that it would raise rates more slowly in 2019.
More likely, the relatively hawkish stance of the Federal Reserve is a reaction to Trump's criticisms of it.
Faced with hostile tweets from the president, Federal Reserve Chair Jerome Powell needs to send a signal that the central bank remains politically independent.
However, after Congress refused to fund his useless Mexico border wall, Trump decided to shut down part of the federal government.
This move put the market into a quasi-panicked state, and soon there were reports that Trump wanted to fire Powell — which could turn market corrections into a crash.
On the eve of Christmas holiday, U.S. Treasury Secretary Steven Mnuchin was forced to make a public statement to calm the market.
He claimed that Trump had no plan to fire Powell and that the U.S. fiscal situation was sound, which precisely highlighted the question of whether the situation was really sound.
Recent internal government personnel changes, which may not necessarily affect economic decision-making, have also caused concern in the market.
White House Chief of Staff John Kelly and Defense Secretary James Mattis are about to leave, and the Trump administration will have no sane people left.
What remains will be all economic nationalists and foreign policy hawks, following Trump's lead entirely.
At present, the possibility of a comprehensive geopolitical conflict with China cannot be ruled out.
A new cold war is highly likely to lead to deglobalization, disrupt global supply chains, but the tech industry will be the first to suffer, as recent cases of ZTE and Huawei clearly demonstrate.
At the same time, Trump seems determined to undermine the cohesion of the EU and NATO amid economic and political instability in Europe.
The investigation by special prosecutor Robert Mueller into the relationship between Trump's 2016 campaign and Russia is the Damocles' sword hanging over Trump's presidency.
Trump is now Dr. Strangelove of the financial markets.
Like the paranoid madman in Stanley Kubrick's classic film, he is trapped in a mutually assured economic destruction.
Now, the market has seen this danger, and the risks of a financial crisis and global recession are rising sharply.
